      "id":"commentisfree/2013/oct/06/help-to-buy-george-osborne-austerity-budget",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T22:22:50Z",
      "webTitle":"Help to Buy: George's marvellous medicine | Editorial",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/06/help-to-buy-george-osborne-austerity-budget",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/06/help-to-buy-george-osborne-austerity-budget",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"28",
        "trailText":"<strong>Editorial: </strong>George Osborne's Help to Buy scheme may be as big of an error as his 2010 austerity budget",
        "headline":"Help to Buy: George's marvellous medicine",
        "body":"<p>This Tuesday George Osborne will make arguably his most significant economic intervention since the austerity budget of June 2010. Sadly, it has all the makings of being just as big an error. Like his cuts plan, Mr Osborne's extension of his <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/help-to-buy-scheme\" title=\"\">Help to Buy scheme</a> comes with an economic justification but is driven by political motivation. The political imperative was again made clear last week when David Cameron, rattled by Ed Miliband's energy-price cap, decided to bring forward the launch of the scheme from next year to this week. For the austerity Conservatives, this is about being seen to be on the voters' side. By no means is this a new theme, but it has taken on an added sharpness and urgency after the conferences.</p><p>It is in this light that <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/borrowing/mortgages/10343793/Help-to-Buy-Key-questions-answered.html\" title=\"\">the coalition's new mortgage market booster</a> should be seen. Until this week, the government's Help to Buy scheme allowed first-time buyers to borrow up to 20% of the value of a new-build home from the government, interest-free for the first five years. The Treasury justified this policy as both helping would-be homeowners on to the housing ladder, and spurring on Barratt's and other giant construction firms to do more building. These explanations cannot apply to this latest extension of Help to Buy.</p><p>As of this week, any household – whether first-time or not – will be able to get help buying any kind of home, whether the paint is still drying or it has been around since George&nbsp;II, worth up to £600,000, as long as they can get together a deposit of 5% of the property value. The government will then provide a guarantee to the mortgage lender of a further 15% of the value. On Tuesday Mr Osborne will lay out further details – such as how much the guarantee will cost lenders (a cost which they&nbsp;will presumably recoup from the customers in higher borrowing rate). And after that, going by what housing market analysts are already saying about interest from would-be buyers, there may well be clouds of dust on British high streets as punters rush to their local estate agents.</p><p>Nearly a quarter-century on from the Lawson boom, stoked by another Conservative chancellor, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/economics-blog/2013/oct/03/uk-economic-boom-could-be-boomlet\" title=\"\">Mr Osborne may well succeed in creating his own boomlet</a>. It may be patchy, it might be temporary, and it may well be dangerous. But the Tories surely hope that it will give them a fighting chance at the next general election, because electoral calculation runs through this policy like words on a stick of rock. Consider: the average price of a property across Britain is £172,000. Yet the government is underwriting purchases on homes worth up to £600,000.</p><p>It may be cynical to suggest that the cap has been set so high to entice wavering voters in key marginals in the pricier property markets of London and the south-east; then again, it may be blunt common sense. One group who will not benefit from Mr Osborne's £12bn intervention are those who cannot save up the 5% deposit. To help them, the government would need to either: improve regulations on landlords and lettings agents (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/18/letting-agents-cowboy-and-cowboy\" title=\"\">when ministers are doing the opposite</a>); provide more social or public housing (some hope); or allow property prices to come down from what remain their stratospheric highs. This policy doesn't help the first two objectives, and it positively blocks the last. Instead, it will push a few more Britons up the housing ladder and then yank that ladder away from the estimated 20% who'll have to fight it out in the underregulated private rented sector.</p><p>From the chancellor who inveighed against Labour's culture of debt and the government that vowed to focus on rebalancing the economy, Help to Buy smacks either of hypocrisy or an admission of defeat. If it works, this policy will get economic growth by luring households to borrow more and pump up Britain's historic housing bubble. What's more, it will subsidise banks to lend on property rather than productive enterprise. Encouraging debt rather than creating jobs, Help to Buy poses as a vote-winner. Perhaps, but it is also an economic dead end.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419201408|2013-10-07T10:21:28Z|9d7f2bb6bdf724e6e1387861f6ea00a5a7f20ce0 -->",
