        "trailText":"<p><strong>Sarah Dropek:</strong> Raising McCain is a small part of her effort to reform a GOP gone mad, but she could change a lot more if she were elected</p>",
        "headline":"Meghan McCain shouldn't be on TV, she should be on a ballot",
        "body":"<p>Meghan McCain has been on a mission to change the GOP, and her series on the Pivot network, <a href=\"http://www.pivot.tv/shows/raising-mccain\">Raising McCain</a>, is her latest effort. The show's curiosity, quick-pace, and uncensored language is fresh for television but won't be changing voter's minds anytime soon. If McCain is going to shift the Republican party to her liking, the best thing she could do is run for office herself.</p><p>As a regular columnist for the Daily Beast, Meghan McCain easily separated her politics from her father, John McCain. In a November 2012 <a href=\"http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/11/16/meghan-mccain-on-why-the-republican-party-needs-to-wake-up.html\">article</a>, Meghan pleads once more with the Republican Party to shift to a more socially liberal, fiscally conservative platform. She writes: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>We can't keep worrying about ultraconservative white male voters. At the end of the day, I still believe I'm on the right side of history, and we can't let this party sink away. We can and we must evolve. </p></blockquote><p>She concludes by threatening that if she doesn't see change soon she might register as an independent in 2016. For someone who has been purported to be the \"<a href=\"http://www.policymic.com/articles/63711/meghan-mccain-is-this-the-new-face-of-the-republican-party\">New Face of the Republican Party</a>\", considering such a switch – <a href=\"http://www.politico.com/blogs/jonathanmartin/0608/Meghan_McCain_gives_Dad_a_special_Fathers_Day_gift.html\">again</a>, after her backing of Kerry in '04 – is pretty heavy intimidation. Yet, she knows both that the party needs her and needs to be more like her. She has <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/video/?/video/bestoftv/2013/09/24/exp-pmt-meghan-mccain-pivot-raising-mccain.cnn\">spoken often</a> about how the GOP needs to reach out to minorities, women, and conservative millenials. Her show is her latest attempt to do that, and bring the party around with her. </p><p>Raising McCain has received some less than stunning <a href=\"http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2013/09/meghan-mccain-takes-feminism-edgy-new-show/69207/\">reviews</a> in its first month of airing. Willa Paskin of Slate <a href=\"http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2013/09/megan_mccain_s_tv_show_raising_mccain_reviewed.html\">takes issue</a> with the broad vagueness of the show and its haphazard format. The New Yorker's Emily Nussbaum comes down hard on the content of the show in a <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/television/2013/09/16/130916crte_television_nussbaum?currentPage=2\">broader review</a> of the full line up for Pivot. But in the context of McCain's career in media, the show appears as a striking effort of a politically active and discontent young Republican to start fresh. </p><p>Her political affiliations are firmly connected to her name and she draws much of her voice in her writing and commentary from it. But the show does not have the same politicized script of her other forays in public debate – highlighting her as the socially liberal Republican desperately fighting for her party. McCain and her editorial team instead chose a different route, exploring timely issues alongside their audience and leaving the politics to be the punchline of a few jokes. </p><p>While she very well could have hosted a show dedicated to exploring what being an \"evolved Republican\" means, the subtlety and beauty of forgoing that option is that the audience is entertained by the \"cast's\" shenanigans, while being reminded from time to time that she is indeed a Republican.</p><p>For a millenial Republican, it's probably refreshing to see someone you can relate to. For a millenial Democrat – like myself – it's intriguing to see what a socially liberal Republican's beliefs can really look like. And for anyone politically minded, the series is a chance to witness the shift in Republicanism that McCain herself has long predicted and demanded. </p><p>That visibility should not be dismissed as trivial. The show, however plagued by poor format, is an important addition to the growing chorus of Republican voices asking for a different party. But a television show on a fledgling network can only go so far.</p><p>McCain has said <a href=\"http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/13/meghan-mccain-sexter-truth-teller-and-now-talk-show-host/?_r=1\">over</a> and <a href=\"http://www.thewrap.com/meghan-mccain-talks-new-show-i-get-heat-for-every-single-thing-i-do/\">over</a> again that she is not interested in running for office. Ever. She cites her lack of tact, indiscriminate past, and her distaste for \"dynastic culture\" in politics. She, however, is in the special position of having the network, ability, and – though dynastic political culture is unfortunate – name credibility needed to successfully run for office. Given her unorthodox beliefs, it is all the more necessary for her to have those resources in order to run in a Republican primary.</p><p>Personally, I'm a great admirer of feminist Audre Lorde. In one of her speeches, she elaborated on her often cited phrase, \"<a href=\"http://lists.econ.utah.edu/pipermail/margins-to-centre/2006-March/000794.html\">the master's tools will never dismantle the master's house</a>.\" Lorde was speaking about racism and feminism, noting that one cannot work within oppressive and intransigent systems in order to subvert them. In this instance I'd argue against that. </p><p>It might be true that it is nearly impossible to dismantle a whole system by working exclusively from within, but if McCain's goal is to radically shift the Republican Party's platform, she could be affecting a heck of a lot more change as an elected official than as a television show host. Raising McCain is a step in the right direction, but I hope McCain decides the next logical step in changing Republicanism is to put her name on a ballot.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418677745|2013-10-07T10:21:28Z|2ec6610b4ff66e6473298549925350203e3eac1e -->",
